[1] Cholera - Haiti (Port-au-Prince)
Date: Mon 17 Nov 2014
Source: UN Office for the Coordination of Humanitarian Affairs (OCHA), ReliefWeb, Alter Presse report [in French, machine trans., edited]
http://reliefweb.int/report/haiti/ha-ti-chol-ra-recrudescence-de-l-pid-mie-dans-l-aire-m-tropolitaine-selon-msf


During a telephone interview with AlterPresse, the humanitarian organization Doctors without Borders (MSF) said it has detected a new outbreak of the epidemic of cholera in the Haitian capital Port-au-Prince and its surrounding area. "There has been a resurgence over the past 1 to 2 months, in particular in Port-au-Prince," said MSF's head of mission in Haiti, Olivier Schulz. "We have more patients than expected," explained Schulz, who believes that the current capacity of MSF is exceeded. On average, MSF's cholera treatment centers receive 50 persons per day, that is, in Delmas (northern periphery) or in Martissant (south sector), but on some days in these last few months the daily total has reached 100.

The Ministry of public health is "motivated and has the will," but the Schulz believes that there is currently a shortage of funding for the management of the epidemic. It called for an "increase in the coordination" of the activities of support for patients, by introducing an active and proactive warning system, able to allow managers to respond more rapidly to outbreaks.

From October 2010 to October 2014, 8621 people died of cholera in Haiti. For this same period, 708 425 cases of cholera have been identified across the country, with 397 637 hospitalized. With a case fatality rate overall of 1.2 percent, Haiti remains the country most affected country by cholera in the world.

